1: Configure the hostnames of SW1 and R1.

2: Configure R1's G0/0 interface and SW1's VLAN1 interface with the indicated IP addresses.

3: Configure the following user account on SW1 and R1:
   username: cisco  /  password: CCNA

4: Configure a DNS domain name of cisco.com on SW1 and R1.

5: Generate the keys that will be used to encrypt  the SSH packets on each device, with a modulus size of 1024.

6: Configure VTY lines 0 through 15 on SW1 and R1 as follows:
   -require the use of the local user database to connect to the vty lines
   -allow only SSH connections to the vty lines
   -terminate connections after 5 minutes of inactivity

7: Enable SSH version 2 on each device.

8: Attempt to connct to each device using SSH from PC1.

Router>en
Router#conf t
Enter configuration commands, one per line.  End with CNTL/Z.
Router(config)#hostname R1
R1(config)#int g0/0
R1(config-if)#ip address 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0
R1(config-if)#no shut
R1(config-if)#exit
R1(config)#username cisco password CCNA
R1(config)#ip domain-name cisco.com
R1(config)#crypto key generate rsa
R1(config)#line vty 0 15
*Feb 28 16:7:28.730: %SSH-5-ENABLED: SSH 1.99 has been enabled
R1(config-line)#login local
R1(config-line)#transport input ssh
R1(config-line)#exec-timeout ?
  <0-35791>  Timeout in minutes
R1(config-line)#exec-timeout 5
R1(config-line)#exit
R1(config)#ip ssh version 2
R1(config)#do wr

Switch>en
Switch#conf t
Enter configuration commands, one per line.  End with CNTL/Z.
Switch(config)#hostname SW1
SW1(config)#int vlan 1
SW1(config-if)#ip add 192.168.1.2 255.255.255.0
SW1(config-if)#no shut
SW1(config-if)#exit
SW1(config)#username cisco password CCNA
SW1(config)#ip domain-name cisco.com
SW1(config)#crypto key generate rsa
SW1(config)#line vty 0 15
*Feb 28 16:7:9.157: %SSH-5-ENABLED: SSH 1.99 has been enabled
SW1(config-line)#login local
SW1(config-line)#transport input ssh
SW1(config-line)#exec-timeout 5
SW1(config-line)#exit
SW1(config)#ip ssh version 2
SW1(config)#do wr

